The government wants to limit the torture of &quot;witches&quot;, published a brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso tend to have several characteristics in common.
They tend to belong to the older generation, they cannot participate in work, for example due to health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
The one who &quot;becomes&quot; a witch is sent into isolation so that she does not threaten the rest of the village.
&quot;It is very rare for a man to meet this fate.&quot;
&quot;Not even young, healthy women are left behind, because they help with work and give birth to children,&quot; describes a nun who takes care of more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their community in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual &quot;social measure&quot;.
She has published an information booklet that should help reduce the witch hunt.
But there is a catch.
&quot;More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,&quot; pointed out the disadvantage of written education, Die Standard newspaper.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, which borders Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week after being tortured, doused with kerosene and set on fire by three women and two men.
The BBC reported on the case.
The perpetrators claim that it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, oil, which is used for ritual anointing, caught fire on the woman.
It allegedly caught fire after the group wanted to &quot;exorcise an evil spirit&quot; from the woman.
The isolation of &quot;witches&quot; is supported by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: &quot;Soul-eaters have always been a danger,&quot; he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to moderate the witch hunt, in The Gambia the president himself took part in it as recently as last year.
&quot;After the death of his aunt, Gambian President Jammi launched a large-scale hunt for witches who were allegedly involved in her death and tried to use black magic to kill the president himself.&quot;
&quot;He enlisted the help of shamans from nearby Guinea, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president&#39;s bodyguards, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president&#39;s farm in Kanilai,&quot; Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the imprisoned people had to drink a herbal potion with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two prisoners did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, almost a thousand prisoners were eventually released.
Bakal&#39;s tenant: He&#39;s drowning in the stove, he signed a higher rent
An older, stocky man stepped out of the door of the client center of the RPG Byty company of &quot;coal baron&quot; Zdenek Bakaly, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm, he carried a folder with new leases for three apartments: his, his daughter&#39;s, and his son, who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation just raised the rent for all three.
Instead of 3,500 per month, the son will pay 4,100 crowns for a second-category 2+1 apartment from next year.
&quot;And there&#39;s no hot water there, and it has to be heated with a petrama (solid fuel stove, editor&#39;s note),&quot; the man points his finger at his son&#39;s new contract, which he has full power to sign.
&quot;But I signed it,&quot; he explains, half annoyed and half resigned.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as &quot;incorrect and immoral,&quot; advises tenants not to sign new contracts and wait until December 7, when they will publish instructions on how to proceed against them.
But the man just waves his hand over it.
&quot;One says this, the other that,&quot; he frowns.
Ostrava is becoming a great laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, the vast majority of apartments that still have non-market rents in the Czech Republic are waiting.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit the &quot;laboratory&quot; in person.
The Havířovská RPG waiting room is one of a total of four in Ostrava and on Tuesday at nine in the morning it is already full.
Right next to the door is a security guard from the security agency with a calling device.
&quot;Rent 2011&quot;, a special button lights up on his touch screen.
One tap and a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
You don&#39;t even have time to read &quot;157&quot; and your number is already beeping on the large display under the ceiling of the waiting room.
It&#39;s your turn in half a second.
After a while, an older married couple comes to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room is apparently not related to the new rents at all.
Most people came to solve common problems as usual - requests for repairs, insurance claims and the like.
In Ostrava, the tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving letters with new leases in their mailboxes since around mid-November.
In letters, RPG Byty proposes to increase the rent by 15 to 38 percent.
A special counter for new leases was opened at the client center on November 18.
&quot;It&#39;s been running for a week, so it&#39;s just getting started,&quot; the worker behind the counter answers after a moment&#39;s hesitation when the client introduces herself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakal&#39;s former mining flats are a hot topic locally.
Before the elections, the Deputy Speaker of the Parliament and Ostrava native Lubomír Zaorálek from the ČSSD took it up quite loudly, and even now the local newspapers are full of it.
&quot;Twenty years after them, I want a new floor.&quot;
&quot;They didn&#39;t even change the damn plate in my toilet,&quot; the man mentioned in the introduction is relieved.
So far, according to the workers, pensioners come the most to see if they will get a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as RPG promises them in the special offer.
Other tenants who sign the new contract by December 15 will also receive a half discount on the February rent.
However, the Havířov &quot;deregulation&quot; desk is definitely not overwhelmed with questions.
&quot;Out of yesterday&#39;s 360 clients, only about forty to fifty people were here because of the rent for 2011,&quot; estimates the worker behind the counter.
At the same time, RPG proposes individual negotiation of contracts on the website and on its bulletin boards where necessary.
However, if the two parties cannot agree on the rent, it will have to be determined by an independent court.
&quot;This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal procedure,&quot; RPG warns on its website.
&quot;Nobody will be judged here,&quot; thinks one of the employees of RPG Byta, and the man on the street in front of the client center agrees with her partially.
&quot;I have a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food, I don&#39;t have to judge myself,&quot; he claims.
However, the employee soon becomes unsettled.
&quot;We&#39;ll see.&quot;
&quot;Mr. Zaorálek is telling them in the media not to sign, so people are probably waiting,&quot; he thinks.
Rent regulation ends in most of the Czech Republic with the New Year 2011, and according to RPG Byta, their increase is an economic necessity.
&quot;The current rent still does not even reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing stock,&quot; reminds Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that the neglect of the housing stock, blamed by the angry tenant, is the main reason for the rent increase, according to the house owners.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPGs could invest four billion in apartments from rents, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it should be 5.2 billion.
The large-screen screen hanging from the ceiling opposite the padded seats of the Havířov waiting room repeats several pieces of information highlighted in red.
&quot;The 2011 rent increase of 15% and less affects 31,200 apartments, that&#39;s more than 90% of RPG apartments.&quot;
&quot;And it will always be at most CZK 7.50 per square meter per month,&quot; appears on the screen.
Only for 400 apartments from the RPG portfolio, the rent will rise by 38 percent.
&quot;In these cases, it is an increase from the extremely low amount of CZK 19.66 per square meter,&quot; warns RPG.
The rent for 2,600 apartments will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive out rents by leaps and bounds, but will be spread over four to eight years.
In addition, he adds another commitment: the company will put all the money from the rent increase (see graph) back into the apartments, mainly into heat savings - new windows and insulation.
People who sign an agreement on rent increases are supposed to get them first.
The offices also include a kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect that it also houses a mini-nursery with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, loads of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees have been able to visit it.
The design-architecture company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings emerged, counted on space for its company mini-kindergarten from the very first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly of baby boomer age, and it was important to her that women designers and architects could quickly return to work.
Together with the possibility of part-time work, the nursery school is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of the social program.
Female builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine a demanding job with childcare.
The mini-school was invented by the employees of Arch.Design themselves, and with the support of the management, they managed to get a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed from the resources of the European Social Fund through the Human Resources and Employment Operational Program and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (subsidy in the amount of 2.8 million CZK), they were able to purchase equipment and facilities and provide qualified staff and operations for a period of two years.
After the financial subsidy has been exhausted (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to operate the mini-school at its own expense for a period of 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year, and the company Economy Rating significantly helped with the application for a subsidy.
Care is provided by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children around the clock, therefore children of any age can attend the nursery school, although most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a &quot;mini-school&quot;, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more may take turns during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of the parents, and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten, regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is about individual education and care, the content of the program in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, they are also provided with quality education - from basic knowledge to preparation for school desks, the English language is also taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and stimulating games, but also with a computer that the children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time, and stressful situations with delayed pick-up of children from nurseries far from the parents&#39; workplace are eliminated.
In this way, parents use working time more productively.
It is not surprising that a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship is created here.
Arch.Design has thus joined the ranks of Czech companies that offer a significant benefit when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly, and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house made of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudí&#39;s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
Such is the Casa Batlló house in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, a scale-like facade and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of Antoni Gaudí&#39;s art nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, soft colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
Upon close observation, one can see geometricity, rhythm and a well-thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is lit up in such a way that the impression of the brilliance of the colors is enhanced even more.
The winding and twisting of shapes appears equally in interiors.
Wood in waves replicates window frames, railings, decorative door elements, peepholes and moldings.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old structure and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí&#39;s idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment building alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated with him.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
A number of other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started Jujola&#39;s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí&#39;s Casa Milá and Park Güell, which contains other works by Gaudí.
Due to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname &quot;House of Bones&quot; from the locals soon after its completion.
Others began to call it the &quot;yawning house&quot; because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows.
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted on the top of the building.
Other sculptural elements of the building also contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house with air vents and typical chimneys.
Their forty-five degree inclination may seem bizarre.
During his work, Gaudí absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city council was horrified by the result and asked for correction.
The councilors were bothered, for example, by the fact that the building&#39;s pillars encroached on the public sidewalk.
The rectification never took place, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the municipality&#39;s call, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two top floors of the building.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social lounge, and on the third floor there were bedrooms and private parts of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house is crossed by a staircase that can be used to climb up to the roof terrace itself.
The fundamental elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social area can be completely connected by opening the salon door, and a larger group can comfortably communicate with each other without at the same time maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to a new facade, the house with Gaudí&#39;s reconstruction also received an unconventional roof and two extra floors.
Gaudí&#39;s play with light is also impressive, with the blue and white glazed tiles lining the inner courtyard and the skylights.
The play of two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the sun&#39;s rays.
The Casa Batlló house, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the building, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided on this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftieth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed with the tours because they found it to be a very profitable business and in addition they expanded the tours to include common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is certainly not negligible, it is 16.50 euros, and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a twenty percent discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you must quickly make friends with one of the residents of the apartment building and visit them directly at home.
How to choose a mattress and bed frame: women have different requirements than men
Not the luxurious bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface, i.e. the mattress and the slats, provide the basis of a really good bed.
However, they must complement each other harmoniously to suit the specific user.
When choosing, many things decide, from weight, height, age, state of health and gender of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and bed frame are made is also important.
A typical example?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages where there is no regular heating, because they &quot;heat up&quot; more slowly.
In addition, they tend to have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
At the same time, it is necessary to turn them regularly.
If they do not have a lot of ventilation channels in the core, and they are still lying on a solid board, they retain moisture: Mold could also appear under them.
Custom also determines the choice.
Anyone who has spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel comfortable on a low bed with a hard surface.
&quot;Perhaps all hockey players returning from the NHL complained to me that they couldn&#39;t sleep here.&quot;
&quot;They needed mattresses with a cushioning layer of lazy foam for their battered shoulders, heels and hips.&quot;
&quot;They are also recommended for people with diabetes who have a disorder of the nervous system, so they do not receive information from the joints and skin,&quot; explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, as well as other customers, therefore searched for mattresses with lazy foam years ago.
&quot;Today it&#39;s fine, Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico have suitable mattresses.&quot;
You don&#39;t have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate lazy suds.
This &quot;miracle&quot; works simply.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape according to the absorbed heat, i.e. it adapts to your warm body.
Nothing pressures you, you won&#39;t roll over at night like after a hard match.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also works as a protection against bedsores.
When choosing a mattress size, add the length of your foot to your height, which is usually about 21 to 34 cm.
A man and a woman with a height of around 180 cm therefore need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, i.e. 180 cm in total.
For single beds, for example singles, at least 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For convenience and a possible visit.
&quot;Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should comfortably have your arms slightly bent at the elbows,&quot; advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, guild master of the Guild of Upholsterers and Decorators, who has been dedicated to the issue of healthy sleep and furniture ergonomics for many years and lectures on it at vocational schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own slat and mattress, but here, be careful when buying to match the heights of the mattresses.
Otherwise, there will be nothing left but to mount the slats at different heights, but you may not be able to do this for every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring frame at least 15, of which count at least three centimeters for the shaping and expanding layer.
&quot;You must not feel the springs when touching your hands or sitting on the mattress,&quot; warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of slat.
Upholstered beds, where the mattress and base are like conjoined Siamese twins, have no business in bedrooms.
Mattresses do not ventilate well, their cover cannot be washed, which is common nowadays.
And since we normally sweat 0.2 to 0.75 l per night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will start to resemble one big (and clogged) strainer.
This is also why experts reject advertising slogans about mattress lifespans of up to 25 years, or even lifetime guarantees.
However, everything has its downsides.
And that&#39;s why practical advice from sellers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, don&#39;t give up on hygiene and a removable cover, but rather add a mattress protector that you can easily remove and wash.
Even though today mattress covers are usually made with zippers all around, so that when unzipped you get two parts (very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), still the handling of the larger types (and with one person) could resemble a fight of lightweights when scanning in the ring with heavy.
Do you have a solid board in your bed instead of a slat?
Never!
Maximum per bed intended for one-night visits.
However, still provide the board (if it does not already have them) with ventilation holes and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (from it. Taschenfederkern) and an expanding layer.
A polyurethane mattress does not belong on such a base.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable for non-positionable slatted slats with 14 to 18 slats, but you will always pay for slats with a larger number of slats, 28 or more, where the slats are doubled in the lumbar area and their rigidity is possible regulate.
Mattresses with a spring frame do not belong to positioning lamella grids, as they do not respond to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, you can also indulge in a so-called shoulder cradle.
It is a special attachment of the slats, which allows you to push or even tilt the slat so that the shoulder of the sleeper is nicely &quot;buried&quot;.
Definitely an important thing for men who have &quot;shoulders across the back&quot;.
It is even remembered by mattress manufacturers who have started to use a softening zone in the shoulder area in &quot;men&#39;s&quot; mattresses.
They also remember women - they treat them with a softer surface in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, wing or plate grates with so-called multi-torsion suspension are intended.
The pressure is distributed to more points and the tension is reduced.
But beware, as soon as you use the wrong pillow (big and &quot;bloated&quot;) on the right mattress and bed frame, most of the &quot;plus&quot; will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the tips should only reach the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
50 x 60 cm is recommended as a suitable size, which is preferred, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should equalize (together with the shoulder cradle of the grid or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
After all, modern mattresses have something in common with the original grass-filled straw bales.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
The trend is simply even for organic mattresses.
The raw materials from petroleum, from which polyurethane foams are made, are replaced by natural oils, for example from safflower and soybean.
Almost all well-known manufacturers use soy.
&quot;Bio in mattresses means that the core is made of material of purely natural origin,&quot; explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers, one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also treat yourself to microcapsules to release the fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There is also a division for men and women.
While the birch plant extract &quot;cools&quot; men so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, the covers &quot;warm&quot; women.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making the weaker sex warmer.
Today&#39;s favorites?
A mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with a broken cellular structure, so it is more breathable than regular polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
By combining different stiffnesses of cold foams and &quot;lazy&quot; foam, multi-zone mattresses are created that know exactly where the head, hips and heels should be.
For a quality mattress, you will pay from 7,000 crowns and above.
Those that meet health parameters tend to have a lower VAT rate and are considered medical devices.
Gumotex was the first in the Czech Republic to achieve this advantage.
It is not easy to save money on a mattress and bed frame.
Sometimes you can take advantage of events from manufacturers or sellers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with Memory foam sewn into the cover for 11,990 crowns.
However, the second one can already be purchased for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cellular structure and high density was started at a &quot;cosmic&quot; pace by the Tempur material.
It was originally created as a material for NASA, because astronauts were exposed to enormous overloads during launches.
Tempur softens in the heat, but hardens in the cold.
It thus perfectly adapts to the warm human body and distributes its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal against the formation of bedsores, but also for increasing comfort while sleeping.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses, but also for medical products, for example for special pillows under the feet, which relieve the legs and the venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents want devices to monitor people, so they want to keep an eye on their children
Fear for their own child leads more and more people to the idea of monitoring via GPS.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also track the movement of people and thus help in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a matchbox, but soon it may be as big as a watch.
A number of people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and started looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
&quot;We are trying to tell everyone that it is not about spying, but about another means of reducing the probability that a tragedy will happen,&quot; says Petr Pilin from the company Macro Weil, which is one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment on the Czech market.
&quot;I accept that in some cases such devices can be misused, for example if they are put in the bag of someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case.&quot;
&quot;Most of the time, customers actually buy it for security reasons,&quot; Pilin added.
According to him, a child should always know what purpose the &quot;box&quot; serves and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear something similar, they will simply get rid of it.
&quot;Even very young children show great creativity in deliberately losing things when they don&#39;t want to be in control.&quot;
&quot;Parents used to have high expectations for cell phones, which can be turned off just like these tracking devices,&quot; says Bočková.
According to her, it is questionable whether such a device would really help in the event of an attack.
&quot;When it comes to a planned abduction, the perpetrator will almost always make sure that the child does not have any electronics that could reveal their location.&quot;
“Now it&#39;s a phone.
&quot;When tracking devices start to proliferate, they will be looking for them too, because their sales will certainly be supported by massive advertising.&quot;
&quot;In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police,&quot; says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can help.
&quot;The device can be set to periodically send the location after a certain period of time.&quot;
&quot;If it were to be damaged, at least the person&#39;s last location would be available.&quot;
&quot;More expensive devices also have built-in inclinometers, so even if a person just slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately send a warning indicating the position,&quot; claims Čech.
According to him, smart mobile phones with navigation can also perform a similar service, where you only need to upload special software.
The problem with current tracking units is that they are either pendant-like devices the size of a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
There is always a risk of losing them.
According to Pilin from Macro Weil, therefore, a device that looks like a regular digital watch is now being tested.
&quot;This will have the greatest advantage in that a potential aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all.&quot;
&quot;Or he will only recognize them after some time and that can give the police extra time,&quot; he adds.
Whether tracking devices evolve into wristbands or pendants, they will still use the same technology used to monitor cars.
It is a combination of determining the location through the GPS system (which is used by common car navigation systems) and the function of a mobile phone, which reports the current position of the car.
The army has incendiary cords that would wrap around the Czech Republic. But it only lasts two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of cords used to detonate explosives.
At the same time, the Ministry of Defense already delivered 224 kilometers of cords to warehouses last year.
The army thus has supplies for 225 years.
The problem is that the durability of the cords is two, maximum four years.
The army bought incendiary cords from the joint-stock company STV Group, as for 40 million crowns.
In justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of detonating cords, the General Staff of the Ministry of Defense wrote TODAY that the soldiers consume 60 kilometers of detonating cords per year during training.
However, it follows from the calculations of army pyrotechnicians that the MF TODAY contacted that all generals, army command officers, secretaries and cleaners would then have to go through very intensive pyrotechnic training every year.
Not excluding Defense Minister Alexander Vondra and Army Commander Vlastimil Pick.
This is the only way to justify the army&#39;s annual consumption of sixty kilometers of fuses.
This length corresponds to 25 thousand explosions.
And even if it really was, the army&#39;s supplies would last more than ten years.
If, on the other hand, it were true that for the basic training of every new professional, a maximum of two meters of incendiary cord is sufficient, as experts say, then the army secured - even with the increased consumption of engineering or special units - supplies for the mentioned 225 years with a fresh purchase.
At the same time, the soldiers of the rapid deployment brigade recently personally complained to Minister Vondr that they have almost no ammunition for handguns, so shooting is also limited due to the lack of money.
Not to mention the lack of underwear.
&quot;It doesn&#39;t bother me either that they repeatedly buy such a large amount of fuses from us.&quot;
&quot;But it&#39;s their decision and they certainly know what they&#39;re going to do.&quot;
&quot;For us, the army is a good customer that we, as traders, try to satisfy,&quot; says Jan Děcký, STV Group&#39;s sales manager.
The spokesman of the Ministry of Defense, Jan Pejšek, justifies the hundreds of kilometers of cord purchased by the fact that the army will have supplies of this &quot;ammunition&quot; for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký from the STV Group only talks about a four-year lifespan of a detonator, and police or army pyrotechnics only about two years.
&quot;With perfect storage, it could even be the four,&quot; says one of them, who, as a soldier, does not want to publish his name due to criticism of the army.
At the end of its useful life, each munition must be carefully tested to ensure that it is still reliable and does not threaten the lives of soldiers.
However, these tests are not free and cost extra money.
Another argument of the ministry is the quantity discount for 445 kilometers of fire cords.
&quot;They cost us sixty percent less than last year&#39;s delivery of two hundred and forty-four kilometers,&quot; explains spokesman Pejšek, explaining the opinion of the buyers of the Ministry of Defense.
Just for comparison: the annual consumption of detonating cords by police pyrotechnicians, who dispose of ammunition from the Second World War or that of the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for several years.
And the police always only order enough to use up this ammunition before its useful life expires.
It worked for her due to the safety of pyrotechnicians, and she can also more flexibly acquire more modern and therefore more reliable types of cords.
Today, the Ministry of Defense is already having considerable difficulties with the disposal of tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for the campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians contacted by MF DNES, the same problem awaits the Czech one in a few years: it will dispose of hundreds of kilometers of old fuses, which it buys &quot;cheaply&quot; today.
