&quot;The Czech Social Security Administration will no longer require an extract from the commercial register during checks on insurance premium payers,&quot; said Jana Buraňová, spokeswoman for the Czech Social Security Administration.
The purpose of the Absurdity of the Year competition is to shed light on all the regulations and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must comply with, and to cancel the meaningless ones.
This is the fourth time this year that it is part of the business competition organized by Hospodářské noviny, and it is increasingly popular among the public.
If last year about three thousand voters took part in the voting, this year there were already almost four thousand of them.
And it&#39;s no wonder, there are still plenty of various legal obligations that only serve to delay business.
&quot;Perhaps we are at the top of the world in terms of the number of tax returns,&quot; says Karel Havlíček from the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Tradesmen of the Czech Republic.
In recent years, the simplification of business has become the declared goal of all governments.
Compared to the rest of the world, however, the situation in the Czech Republic is not particularly improving.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranked 74th in terms of business conditions, which is eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was first announced in 2006 and runs according to the same scenario every year.
Anyone can submit administrative and bureaucratic nonsense every year from April to the end of September, when the competition closes.
To register, use the web address www.firmaroku.cz. After that, the organizer of the competition will select seven candidates for the &quot;anti-price&quot; and let the public vote on it during October via the Internet at www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that gets the most votes wins.
More than a hundred, more precisely 105 meaningless regulations and ordinances were entered into this year&#39;s survey.
Tips were sent by entrepreneurs, as well as professional associations and journalists.
Among the &quot;finalists&quot; of the competition, the nominees included, for example, the demand that cars for the maintenance of highways and expressways pay tolls, or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two toilets paint every two years.
The list of this year&#39;s seven proposals is published on the competition website.
The announcement of the competition, which always takes place at the beginning of November at Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of a happening that is regularly attended by personalities from political and social life.
