&quot;Economic prosperity cannot work where the state throws sticks under the feet of entrepreneurs, that&#39;s why my goal is to abolish at least three dozen paragraphs every year, which today only unnecessarily complicate business,&quot; said Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
The effort to abolish senseless regulations does not sound in vain.
In 2007, people were most bothered by the entrepreneur&#39;s obligation to report three days in advance to the trade office in the place where the permanent establishment is located, the intention to take the stand to an exhibition or a pilgrimage.
This obligation was removed by an amendment to the Trade Act.
The second most voted obligation in 2007, which was to report to the labor office for a foreign employee a business trip of up to 30 days, was removed by the so-called green card law.
And until the third, all the best.
The absurdity of 2009 was the order for physiotherapists to have a large mirror, a refrigerator and two step-on scales in their office.
This was eased this year by a decree of the Ministry of Health - the obligation to have a refrigerator was abolished.
