Households pay hundreds more per month for housing
Starting in January, households will have to pay extra not only for all types of energy, but also for water and sewage, heat supplies, and rents will rise somewhere.
From January, families will have to take hundreds of crowns more out of their wallets than they do now.
Electricity will become more expensive by up to 4.6 percent, gas will be about 2 percent more expensive, in some cities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supplies, and in many places, central heating supplies will also become more expensive.
The increase in electricity prices should cost households in apartments hundreds of crowns more per year than they do now.
At the same time, the prices of power electricity have been reduced by all the main suppliers, so the significant increase in support for the production of energy from renewable sources, especially photovoltaics, is to blame.
Gas will be slightly more expensive, but at a time when people heat the most and thus have the highest consumption.
So they also have to count on hundreds of extra crowns every year.
While electricity and gas will become more expensive across the country, the change in central heating prices varies from place to place.
Price increases are mainly planned by larger municipalities.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about 50 crowns more per month for central heating from January, families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 crowns a year.
In turn, the residents of Prague are threatened with more than 9 percent more expensive water and sewage services, if the city increases the rent from the infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, Pražené will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
However, the price in Prague will still be among the lower in the national comparison.
In the north of Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, the price of water and sewage is to increase by 7.4 percent.
For example, rent prices in 450,000 rental apartments, where regulation ends in January, may increase significantly.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns about 2,500 apartments in Ústí nad Labem, intends to increase the rent by up to one hundred percent from January.
Those who do not agree with the new rent amount intend to take the company to court.
Regulated rents paid by people in approximately 300,000 apartments could rise by up to ten percent next year.
Czech children get drunk on fernet and rum. Beer is out of fashion, it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka, exceptionally even a better brand of whiskey stolen from the parents.
These are the drinks after which drunkards under the age of fifteen most often end up in the care of doctors.
Children are no exception, who are repeatedly treated in the hospital for epilepsy.
It follows from the experience of doctors who encounter similar cases at the reception of children&#39;s departments of hospitals.
&quot;Some beers or wines are completely unfashionable because they take a long time to get drunk.&quot;
&quot;The trend is definitely hard alcohol,&quot; Luděk Pelikán, head of the children&#39;s department of Hořovice Hospital in Central Bohemia, told Práv.
&quot;When they manage to get a bottle for dad out of the cupboard, it&#39;s probably whiskey, but otherwise fernet and vodka prevail.&quot;
&quot;Vodka has the advantage that they pour it into juice and it doesn&#39;t smell so much,&quot; explained the primary.
And Eva Jurinová, the spokeswoman for the Motol University Hospital, agrees with him.
&quot;Most often it&#39;s fernet or rum.&quot;
&quot;That&#39;s modern alcohol today, especially in elementary schools.&quot;
&quot;In some cases, it was slivovica that they brought from home,&quot; said Jurinová.
According to Principal Pelikán, 13- or 14-year-old drinkers on hospital admissions are a relatively common phenomenon.
Before Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for ten years in pediatrics in Motola, where ambulances bring over-excited schoolchildren from the wider area.
“One girl slept with us about four times.
&quot;She started her career at the age of twelve, when she was brought to us with an additional 3.5 per thousand of alcohol in her blood combined with ecstasy,&quot; the doctor described a particularly serious case.
&quot;She was at the fairgrounds in Holešovice for some dance party.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s interesting that her mother didn&#39;t think it was strange at all that she didn&#39;t know about her daughter for 48 hours,&quot; the primary teacher marveled.
It is the disinterest of parents or even their considerable tolerance for the drinking of their own offspring that is considered to be the main cause of increasing child drinking.
However, according to experts, it is impossible to talk about addiction in the true sense of the word in children.
&quot;The term alcoholic means a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that belong to it, and this is not the case with children.&quot;
&quot;Those who use alcohol repeatedly tend to have an unsuccessful family and social background,&quot; explained Primary Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, around forty drunken children were hospitalized at the pediatric clinic in Motola this year until mid-November.
However, only those with severe intoxication who had to stay in the hospital are included in the statistics.
Child drunkards who are taken away by their parents after outpatient treatment, or taken home by the police, are not counted in any way.
Aside from when kids just sit down after school and drink a bottle of brandy, according to Pelikan, there are three seasonal swings you can count on: Halloween, New Year&#39;s Eve and the end of the school year.
&quot;They either drink away the grief of a bad report card or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays.&quot;
&quot;Of course, at the witches&#39; reception, I also saw seven child drunkards at the same time,&quot; Pelikán pointed out.
A drunkard who spends the night detoxing under the supervision of doctors is paradoxically at an advantage compared to the one who suffers an unpleasant hangover at home the next day.
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose will be banished by a watering infusion with glucose and nutrients that the body lacks.
&quot;They are actually better off, because they have a good awakening after the beautiful evening experience and they are not in pain.&quot;
&quot;They&#39;re just confused about where they are,&quot; Pelikán admitted, adding that he sometimes spoils the patients&#39; pleasant mood by at least listing the costs of their treatment.
Ambulance transport and hospitalization in an emergency bed can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
&quot;Sometimes I used it as an educational tool, when I directly calculated to the children during the visit how much their drunkenness cost and that they could also spend the whole summer working part-time to earn money for that one party,&quot; added Pelikán.
However, according to him, health insurance companies do not approach recourse proceedings in which the parents would recover the costs of treatment in cases of child drunkards.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defense exchanged the Casa C-295M transport aircraft, flew to Seville, Spain, where the manufacturer of the Casa aircraft - EADS, is based on Tuesday.
It is the first time that machines of this type appeared in the possession of someone other than the Czech army.
So far, they have only been abroad for exercises or demonstration flights.
These are two-seater versions of the L-159T1, which were previously operated by the Czech army and which were airworthy.
The remaining three machines are single-seat L-159s.
They are still preserved in Aer Vodochody, and the trade intermediary - the company Omnipol - took them over last week.
According to Jan Pejšek from the defense press department, it is not yet known when the planes will be physically dispatched from Vodochod.
&quot;Single-seater L-159 aircraft for the shift were allocated from long-term stored aircraft, without additional deposits and investments from the department of the Ministry.&quot;
&quot;The two-seater L-159T1s were exchanged in their current state and form,&quot; Pejšek told Právu.
He added that the army will not be left without two-seater aircraft, because in May 2009 the ministry signed a contract worth 200 million crowns with Aer Vodochody to convert four unnecessary L-159 machines into two two-seater machines.
One new aircraft was taken over by the army in July, the other will be taken over by the end of this year.
According to Pejšek, EADS has committed to introduce the aircraft into the armament of some alliance countries.
&quot;The contract clearly states that the customer of the L-159 aircraft is EADS and they will be used to train pilots from NATO countries.&quot;
&quot;Therefore, it is up to the customer how he will implement this,&quot; said Pejšek.
Hospodářské noviny reported some time ago that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
Last year, the government of Mirek Topolánek approved the exchange of five L-159s for one Casa aircraft and the purchase of three additional aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns.
The Ministry of Defense did not call for a tender for the purchase and approached EADS directly.
The defense leadership at the time argued that the exchange would support the future export of the L-159 abroad.
