A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than their ring finger are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
That&#39;s the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
&quot;Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men under the age of 60,&quot; said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick&#39;s Institute of Cancer Research.
The finger could thus help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially when combined with genetic risk or other risk factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and simultaneously more than three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger on their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to develop prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those whose index finger was longer than their ring finger, this risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men in their 60s the drop was even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone equals a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that promotes the growth of prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows about this study in passing, but he does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer is &quot;completely proven&quot;.
