Common practice of democracy
Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Criminal activity is a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen by many regions as more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current Latinobarómetro survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can track changes in attitudes across the entire region.
Two related things dominate this year&#39;s survey, which took place in September and early October.
The first is that Latin America is in a relatively cheerful mood.
The second is increasing the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific Rim in South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a deep drop in output last year.
But only about half of those polled in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are convinced Democrats, pulling the regional average down (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but a large increase compared to 2001, when it was 25% ( chart 3).
Around 34% said they trusted their country&#39;s parliament and 45% trusted the government, again the same numbers as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
The support arose during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latinos living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year to 32%.)
However, the mood varies widely from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil&#39;s strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since the surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem (see Chart 5).
Around 31% say that either they themselves or a close relative have been a victim of crime in the past year, but this is down from 38% last year and is also the lowest figure since 1995.
Stronger economic performance is reflected in growing support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that a market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage increased from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela share the same opinion (and 80% there support private business), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the area, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, up from 11% last year )
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
