Arsenic-resistant microbes raise the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the search for new life forms on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, and they say it&#39;s a sign that life has possibilities that stand outside of the main elements that have so far been considered fundamental.
“This organism has a dual ability.
&quot;It can grow on either phosphorus or arsenic.&quot;
&quot;This fact is very strange, but it is not proof that this is some form of truly &#39;alien&#39; life,&quot; commented Paul CW Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur - were considered necessary for life.
However, the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after phosphorus is substituted for arsenic.
&quot;You start to wonder what else is possible,&quot; said Arizona State University&#39;s Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report.
The finding is significant for the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a news report published to discuss it, which did not reveal details of the find, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It is not so.
The discovery &quot;shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we think of as &#39;standard&#39; may not be so absolutely necessary for life,&quot; explained Charles Cockell, professor at Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, Great Britain.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
&quot;This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure,&quot; added Cockell.
It wasn&#39;t a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA&#39;s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she reasoned that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to substitute one for the other.
&quot;Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus.&quot;
&quot;As a result, organisms have a very hard time separating these elements from each other.&quot;
&quot;However, arsenic is so different that it doesn&#39;t work like phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes,&quot; Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt to and grow.
Microbes grow better when exposed to phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, it raises the possibility that a life form that uses arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon. where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus is not new, but no example has ever been found to prove this fact.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculate that earlier life forms may have used it.
&quot;This suggests that there may have been other ways to form life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth period,&quot; said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health
