Can politeness bridge the gap?
After a campaign notable for its profanity and negativism, there has been little civility in Washington this week.
Is this the first swallow of real cooperation between the two political parties or just an illusory moment before a quick return to the party struggle in the capital?
Tuesday&#39;s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no major breakthroughs on the major issues that must be discussed during the session.
But in any case, this was a polite discussion addressing the differences of opinion between the two parties, as well as defining their shared responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of partisan infighting.
Wednesday&#39;s public meeting of the president&#39;s deficit commission was also civil, despite political differences that remain among members.
It seems clear that working closely together over several months has built a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still divides the members.
And it is quite difficult to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both parties are now in a trial period - probing each other for signs of collegiality and compromise, while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and voters&#39; patience with renewed partisan warfare.
Therefore, Tuesday&#39;s meeting and its later evaluation by the participants was carried out with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too wide and too deep to suggest a quick reversal of the conditions that have prevailed here for the past two years.
Whether it&#39;s taxes, spending, health care or rights, the two sides are miles apart.
Nevertheless, Washington prepared the November elections quickly, to say the least.
&quot;It&#39;s not a question of whether the regulatory issues have changed,&quot; said Pete Wehner, a Bush administrator now with the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
&quot;These are inevitable after the elections.
