Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Much like the likely compromise on unemployment benefits only because Republicans can&#39;t watch them support tax cuts for the wealthy while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After Tuesday&#39;s meeting at the White House, there is already more optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of a new opening agreement.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution cautions that successful cooperation on major issues will not necessarily lead to a bipartisan relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable, he said.
&quot;After the things that have to be done are done, in the short term psychology will return to one of confrontation,&quot; he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism—which is largely widespread—that politeness will lead to genuine cooperation.
&quot;I look at everything between now and 2012 as a shadow box where the major events will happen in 2012,&quot; he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the formation of a new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters who helped create it.
Now faced with the danger of exaggeration, Republican leaders know they must follow through on their promises to cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
Those partisan lines are clear in the initial reactions to the deficit recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and are, in their view, pushing the deficit issue onto the public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to present their plan as an official recommendation, and are fighting to get as close to that number as possible.
The greatest resistance is among elected officials on the panel, who suggest that we have, at least today, little basis or will for compromise when it comes to financial issues.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House and House Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of partisan conflict as Republicans challenge Obama to tackle the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater party cooperation.
What causes the shift?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that despite the partisanship of the last election, most Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If it could be headed for a stalemate, as it was in 1995, then both sides will be watching the public&#39;s reaction very carefully.
Anyone threatened with a vote reduction is likely to change course and seek a compromise.
That may be an optimistic view of things.
Partisanship and alignment are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and a greater ideological divide appears to have developed between Obama and House Republicans than there was between the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to more important elections in 2012.
Based on that reality, the civility that emerged this week would be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
