During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its soldiers fled to Cambodia&#39;s border with Thailand.
There they started an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary ran guerrilla wars from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, following a UN-sponsored peace deal, the country was led to its first democratic elections in 1993. Large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the government, culminating in the surrender of Ieng Sara in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who persevered, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters sank into ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them nostalgically remember the days of the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge have retained their local government position in exchange for their weapons, their position remains tenuous as unskilled farmers.
&quot;These people benefited minimally from the surrender,&quot; said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
&quot;They are surrounded by the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime.&quot;
“They were brought up without any idea of doing business.
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungles around Anlong Veng before settling down as a poor farmer in 1998.
&quot;Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,&quot; he said.
“Ta Mok fed everyone.
“But now life is hard because we have to provide everything ourselves.
The ongoing trial of the Khmer Rouge also raised concerns.
Early next year, the court will begin investigating Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court has a mandate to prosecute the masterminds and people responsible for the crimes, but has not said whether it will pursue the four cases.
It did little to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a regional leader in Banteay Meanchey province during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Documentation Center in Cambodia that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers are believed to have died.
On a recent steamy evening, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her wooden house on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun began to set and shadows appeared across the parched grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about her past with the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to go.
&quot;Cambodia is peaceful and stable,&quot; she said.
&quot;If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.&quot;
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned of instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians disagree.
&quot;Cambodia must dig a deep hole and bury the past in it,&quot; he said.
But confronting the past is just what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
&quot;Reconciliation in the Khmer context means putting the broken pieces back together,&quot; he said.
“It is our duty to put these broken pieces back together so we can understand each other.
The center published the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, 75 pages long and titled &quot;History of Democratic Cambodia.&quot;
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to a Ministry of Education history textbook that contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
Like many people in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng knew few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the town&#39;s association with the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he took the book home to study.
&quot;My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the courts,&quot; he said.
&quot;They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute.&quot;
Such opposition makes the reconciliation process more complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, textbooks and the courts are starting to have an impact, he continued.
The Khmer Rouge still have a strong charm here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, a road overgrown with weeds and littered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black soot covered by a rusted tin roof.
Pol Pot&#39;s body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside mobile phone seller, said she did not know much about the man who was cremated at the site.
&quot;But he has a strong spirit, many local people come here and pray to him,&quot; she said.
It was Nuom Sothea&#39;s birthday and she planned to visit Pol Pot&#39;s resting place later, where she would bring a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope that it would bring her good luck.
Belarus agrees to divest its stockpile of uranium-based weapons
In a surprise victory in President Obama&#39;s campaign to secure nuclear material around the world, the government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it will give up its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The agreement was announced in a joint statement issued after a security summit by Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton and Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov.
The U.S. government has been trying to convince Belarus to give up highly enriched uranium for years, and they appeared to have hit a stumbling block last spring.
But U.S. officials told The Washington Post that a pair of covert operations were conducted with Belarus in the past two months to remove 187 pounds of uranium-based weapons from a Belarusian research facility.
That set the stage for Wednesday&#39;s deal to remove the rest of the material — about 500 pounds, according to the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity because the matter is sensitive.
The agreement proved to be one of the most important outcomes of Obama&#39;s 47th National Nuclear Security Summit in April, from which Belarus was excluded.
And it was apparently a good move to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the subsequent summit in 2012.
&quot;I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit.&quot;
&quot;This proves that the process is working,&quot; said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for Global Security, a nuclear security advocacy group.
Clinton called the deal a &quot;very significant, important step&quot; by Belarus.
Obama promised in Prague in April 2009 that he would secure all sensitive nuclear materials around the world within four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries get rid of all their stockpiles of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be seventh.
A dozen countries did so during the George W. Bush administration.
At the time of Obama&#39;s nuclear security summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko announced that his nation would never give up its uranium.
&quot;We have highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially the basis for a weapon and less enriched uranium,&quot; Lukashenko said afterwards.
“It&#39;s our commodity...We&#39;re not going to make dirty bombs, and we&#39;re not going to sell it to anybody.
&quot;We&#39;re just using it for research purposes, that&#39;s all.&quot;
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago and expressed interest in reaching an agreement.
The first commitment to remove Belarus&#39; uranium in October was particularly complicated because the material was lightly irradiated, officials said.
It was loaded onto a special train that traveled more than 1,300 miles to a Russian storage and disposal facility, officials said.
The second operation was concluded on Monday and was carried out by air, officials said.
The US government has spent $13 million on the program, most of it to supply a Belarusian research institute with low-enriched uranium, which is not suitable for making nuclear weapons.
&quot;Everything was coordinated very carefully and managed on the basis of trust&quot; that led to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, an Energy Department official working for Global Threat Reduction.
The James Martin Center for the Study of Nuclear Nonproliferation estimated this year that Belarus has at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium.
Belarus will, according to the joint statement, aim to eliminate its stockpile by 2012.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, largely due to Lukashenko&#39;s brutal crackdown on human rights.
But Wednesday&#39;s statement suggests the possibility of a gradual thaw.
&quot;Welcoming progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus have recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains the basis for improving mutual relations and is necessary for the progress of the country and its people,&quot; he said.
