On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which runs counter to the idea of upholding old traditions held by much of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first of them is represented by a strong euro zone, which would include Germany, but also, for example, Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the marque - although it may seem like science fiction now, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third possibility, according to the German proposals, is the reworking of the euro with greater macroeconomic supervision, budgetary rigor, fines for guilty states, possible payment deferrals for some of them, and the extension of the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
