Sport and circumventing the rules
Feints like Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show intelligence, not an intention to escape punishment.
The alleged orchestrated suspensions of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on November 23rd has caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this was unsportsmanlike conduct and whether or not UEFA should ban both footballers punish.
Famously, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the named players one by one deliberately wasted time when a foul was about to be played, in order to provoke the referee, who showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will serve their punishment in the following match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing top of their group - and will be able to proceed to the next stage without their cards.
In the end, UEFA&#39;s disciplinary committee handed coach José Mourinho a two-match ban and the offending players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, i.e. the rules that are unwritten but followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that the team Real Madrid (who boast of nobility and honor in their anthem, and who have already fined their players for similar actions) were involved, and also, it seems, due to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adding another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
in any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of action, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is in conflict with the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts circumvent the law; these are indeed events respecting sports rules, the meaning of which, however, seems to be being circumvented.
What type of damage such actions do to the spirit of sportsmanship is addressed.
One of the requisites of sportsmanship is the physical inviolability of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, i.e. there was no violent play.
Another of these essentials of fair play is to avoid giving players an advantage over the opposing team due to their offense - which did not happen here.
So the paradoxical thing about the action of the Real Madrid players is the fact that there was not what we normally characterize as trickery or circumvention of the law, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid a sanction, but this behavior should have been as visible as possible in order to receive a penalty.
They waited and were happy to receive the punishment.
Another question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have from their intentional offense.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that no benefit is achieved in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it&#39;s not even a useful strategy for the next match, since the club won&#39;t be able to count on these players.
The advantage is obviously that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could jeopardize their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first sight the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by doing this, the players will get rid of the penalty, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in round one.
So as the rounds go on it won&#39;t be entirely clear if this is an advantage.
In short and well, these negotiations do not go against the spirit of sportsmanship, part of which is to make strategic decisions that allow for maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case at hand, the players did not aim to avoid the penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or running from punishment.
Although the line between ingenuity and circumventing the rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly ingenuity.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions to provoke them were transmitted from the management.
Damage to sporting principles by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
