The United States is changing its visa rules
People will need to contact the Visa Applicant Services centers before the interview at the Consular Section; costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
Effective January 10, 2011, the visa processing process at United States Embassies and Consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact Visa Applicant Services centers (abbreviated from English ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
ASC personnel will collect the applicant&#39;s biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including:
The total cost of processing a visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for arranging an appointment, another for processing the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant pays only one fee that covers all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa-on-application cases (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for a business and investor visa.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to go through an interview with a consular officer, but just go to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and be fingerprinted.
As biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants requiring a second interview appointment at the Consular Section will spend less time there than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application process, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
