According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace incandescent light bulbs, which still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market, with compact fluorescent light bulbs or, even better, light emitting diode (DEL or &quot;LED&quot; in English) light bulbs, a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt ) GES emissions on the planet due to lighting would break down.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the entire planet&#39;s car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GHG emissions to drop from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But another 5 Gt will have to be subtracted from this balance in order to stabilize climate warming at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 so that it can be ruled out that it does not get out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluorescent compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with new bulbs with DEL, we will reduce this consumption by two more.
Fluorocompact bulbs last from 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
New DEL bulbs, such as those put into production this week by Philips - the company is said to have participated in the UN study - have an expected lifespan of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving us an idea of the potential savings with a replacement plan that would apply in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
