Vengeful hackers and malicious spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is exposed, a scandal that seems scandalous only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens, and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and anticipates a future dominated by regression.
But let&#39;s proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by a secret service (of any nation) consists entirely of press clippings.
The Americans&#39; &quot;extraordinary revelations&quot; about Berlusconi&#39;s sex life are announcing what everyone has been able to read for months in any newspaper (all but the two Berlusconi owns), and the sickly caricature profile of Gaddafi has long been the subject of sketches for cabaret artists.
The rule that classified documents may consist only of news already known is fundamental to the dynamics of the Secret Service, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Freemasons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to search for new information (he does not even know where to look for reports about non-existent ones), but because those who are engaged in the occult believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have already learned .
This is Dan Brown&#39;s success mechanism.
The same goes for classified documents.
The whistleblower is lazy, and a lazy (or narrow-minded) intelligence chief (and if he isn&#39;t, he could be an editor at the newspaper Libération, for all I know) who only believes what he admits to be true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi that the US embassy sent to the State Department was the same that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why was there such a fuss about the revelations about these documents?
On the one hand, they are saying what every cultured person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II and the time when heads of state can talk on the phone or take a plane to have dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation were transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows very well that this is seemingly ignored out of hypocrisy.
However, the fact that it is being repeated publicly defies the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most highly classified information of the most powerful country in the world represents a hard blow, not insignificant, for the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victims and its &quot;perpetrators&quot;.
But let&#39;s go from there to the deep truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in the days of Orwell, it was possible to hold all power, like some kind of Big Brother who controlled his people&#39;s every move.
Orwell&#39;s prophecy has been proven since the ability to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway used and so on, has made the citizen a total victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the &quot;tombs&quot; with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the intervention of some hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker - chosen as the citizen&#39;s avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets be maintained?
It is true that Georg Simmel already said that a true secret is a contentless secret (and a contentless secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all the information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is really a mysterious empty secret because it is taken out of public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton&#39;s secrets were empty secrets is to strip him of all power.
WikiLeaks did nothing wrong with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something great for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow to a power so significant?
It is clear that in the future states will not be able to send sensitive information online - this would be equivalent to publishing it on a poster stuck on a street corner.
But it is also abundantly clear that with current technology it is useless to hope that a message over the phone can be kept secret.
There is nothing easier than finding out if and when the head of state traveled by plane and connected with one of his colleagues.
How will private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future?
I know very well that for the moment my forecast belongs to science-fiction and is therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials who are transported discreetly through uncontrollable routes, carrying only those messages that they know by heart or, rather, hiding rare information in the heel of the shoe.
The information will be kept in unique copies in keyed drawers: all in all, the attempted espionage in the Watergate affair was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet rehabilitated the wire-based (telephone) telegraph.
Videocassettes (analog) allowed moviegoers to take a movie step by step, move it forward and backward and reveal all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow you to jump by chapters, that is, by macro portions.
Via high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while it takes three and a half hours to travel by plane and the transport it involves.
So it is not unusual for politics and communication techniques to return to horse-drawn wagons.
One last note.
At other times, the press tried to understand what was being plotted in the secrecy of the embassy.
Now it&#39;s the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacked its funding pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test the compliance with the promises of rapidly unblocked financing (so-called fast start or early financing) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks were exposed
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010-2012.
The European Union promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, and France 1.26 billion euros (that is, 420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU pulled out a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment regarding fast start funding: a report detailing the action of its member states, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do the same and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its 2012 pledge of €7.2 billion.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are &quot;new and additional&quot; under the Copenhagen Accord to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what &quot;new and additional&quot; means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonization, some member states, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered the year 2009 as a reference: international funding was preserved and it added 150 million to it for three years under the title of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment terms or with terms at the level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of &quot;all new projects&quot; in 2010 are &quot;new and additional&quot;.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Development Aid d&#39;Aide publique au développement.
Specifically, France&#39;s overall aid to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease), to comply with its commitment to finance &quot;new and additional...
Another decisive element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 borrowed equals €1 donated.
Obviously, it is difficult to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be proven for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as equivalent to one euro that we give... , they should not have we would understand it from the title of our obligations, but as the price of the loan for the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only give this justification: it &quot;respects&quot; its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% is a donation (36.1 million euros) - see the document EU so you can check for yourself.
It is the only EU country that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany requested 46% from there, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) keep their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 in satisfaction of their promise, France gives only 10 centimes and considers this effort comparable.
A beautiful piece of juggling!
To sum up, in its &quot;fast start&quot; financing, France is operating with a double sleight of hand: on the one hand with the development of the stock over time and on the other with the real financial burden.
Although it only spends 36.1 million euros, it manages to convince that it is spending 420 million euros &quot;new and additional&quot; in relation to its promises.
Manipulation of the finance minister (since it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative effect, both inside the EU (why would member states continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and in the negotiations, because the developing countries are not completely naive...
The early funding chapter is just a small question, relatively short-lived, in relation to the series of climate discussions.
But she could be an extra grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully that won&#39;t be the case for us.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounting records for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its obligations and decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid the discussion about deposits in long-term financing (another important chapter currently being discussed): we will not escape the question of &quot;additionality&quot; or the method of accounting for loans.
France should change its attitude to become as progressive on these deposits as it is on others.
So everyone is pinning their hopes on the new Environment Minister, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
The surprise announcement of France&#39;s fast start and its vision of &quot;additionality&quot; and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
Alarm about pesticides ingested by children.
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study released this Wednesday by the Future Generations Association (ex-Movement for the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which points out that its results &quot;do not have a significant statistical value in view of the low number of analyzed samples, but are characteristic of the issue being processed&quot;, bought between July and September food normally consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack per child for about ten years in supermarkets in l&#39;Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including the official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as sweets, were analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are considered carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five substances are clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could interfere with the endocrine glands (PE) , according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
&quot;Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we can clearly see that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminating substances, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking&quot;, the association states.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
An apple imported from Brazil, presented by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, among others, a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, in which studies have found traces of powerful insecticides banned in the EU.
Additionally, ground beef, canned tuna, and even buns and gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was the &quot;richest&quot; with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not escape analysis.
The ultimate risk to consumers of this &quot;cocktail of contaminants&quot; is likely to be underestimated,&quot; the study concluded.
The association Ecological Europe-Greens (EE-LV) proposed &quot;in the face of an urgent situation&quot; to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the &quot;increase of the diseases of civilization&quot;.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the status of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
